{
    "level": "sentence",
    "abstract": [
        {
            "text": "The fragmentation fractions of c and b quarks into the weakly decaying charmed hadrons D 0 , D + , D + s and + c , and into the charmed vector meson D * + have been derived from the LEP measurements and averaged.",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 1
        },
        {
            "text": "The c quark fragmentation fractions represent probabilities to hadronise as a given charmed hadron, while the b quark fragmentation fractions are defined as sums of probabilities to produce a particular charmed hadron or its antiparticle.",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 1
        }
    ],
    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "Introduction",
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "Charmed mesons are produced in processes of charm quark fragmentation and in decays of bottom hadrons. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The large values of the c and b quark masses allow using the perturbative QCD (pQCD) calculations for describing the heavy quark production. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "However, to describe completely the heavy quark transition into a given hadron, a non-perturbative parametrisation tuned to experimental results is needed. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "Fragmentation functions, used to parametrise a transfer of quark's energy to a given hadron, are expected to be rather different for different pQCD calculations [1][2][3]. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 161,
                    "end": 164,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b0",
                    "text": "[1]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 164,
                    "end": 167,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b1",
                    "text": "[2]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 167,
                    "end": 170,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b2",
                    "text": "[3]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Fragmentation fractions are probabilities for c/b quark to hadronise as a particular charmed/bottom hadron, f (c \u2192 H c )/ f (b \u2192 H b ). ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The fragmentation fractions of b quark to a particular charmed hadron, f (b \u2192 H c ), can be defined similarly representing convolutions of the f (b \u2192 H b ) fractions and branching fractions of the bottom hadrons into a given charmed hadron. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "For heavy quark (Q) production at large energies far from the QQ threshold, the fragmentation fractions are often assumed to be universal.",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "Charm and bottom quark production in e + e \u2212 annihilations provides the cleanest environment for the heavy quark fragmentation measurements. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 5,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "Charm",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w0"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "A compilation of charm fragmentation fractions was performed in 1999 [4] using available at a e-mail: gladilin@mail.cern.ch that time published and preliminary LEP measurements in Z decays as well as the results obtained at centre-of-mass energies of about 10 GeV. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 69,
                    "end": 72,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b3",
                    "text": "[4]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "In this article, the fragmentation fractions of c and b quarks into the weakly decaying charmed hadrons D 0 , D + , D + s and + c , and into the charmed vector meson D * + , derived from the final LEP results, are presented. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The measurements at centre-of-mass energies of \u223c10 GeV are not included in this compilation because they can be affected by exclusive production channels, such as e + e \u2212 \u2192 D ( * )+ D ( * )\u2212 [5], and threshold effects.",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 191,
                    "end": 194,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b4",
                    "text": "[5]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The LEP measurements, used in this article, were based on the charmed hadron decays summarised in Table 1. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 98,
                    "end": 105,
                    "type": "table",
                    "text": "Table 1"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Results of all measurements have been updated using new branching fractions of the above decays. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "For all decays, except + c \u2192 p K \u2212 \u03c0 + , the current world average values [6] of the branching fractions are used. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 74,
                    "end": 77,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b5",
                    "text": "[6]"
                }
            ]
